</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ayerishstormcaller>Ayerish Stormcaller</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lonely in Kera Ridge</span><br>  Posts: 189<br> <font color=#628CBC>(11/25/02 2:19:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=281.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   .</span><hr size=1> Actually yes, I have several friends who are Muslims, and we talk about these kinds of things often.  I'm fairly objective with them about religion in general and there's plenty of mutual respect--they're about evenly split on the issue of militant Islamic doctrine.  Half of them think it's abhorrent, and half of them think that the world needs to change, and if it takes a few thousand innocent lives to bring about that change and reset the balance of power, then that's a justifiable sacrifice in their eyes.  Frighteningly, the ones that feel that the change needs to come about &quot;by any means necessary&quot; are the ones from upper-middle class backgrounds who have never really known true suffering.<br>
<br>
You're misreading my point of view.  I'm not lobbying for women's rights in Muslim countries, or racial equality.  What I'm saying is that Muslims need to stop massacring innocent people in the name of their God.  No, of course not all of them participate.  But I am hard-pressed to state that, on a global scale, that it's only a &quot;minority&quot; of the Muslim faithful that feel this way.  Clearly Islamic extremists have even less confidence in diplomacy than I do; their response is to bomb, murder, or throw rocks at things they don't like.  My point is that, like it or not, sooner or later someone is going to throw a *really really big* rock, unless somebody ELSE steps in and stops the rock throwing for good.  Probably a poor metaphor, but I hope you get my point.<br>
<br>
Non-intervention is no longer an option, because it's boiling down to an Us vs. Them issue.  Us is not Christians or Americans, nor is Them Muslims or Arabs, but there's a line between sanity/civilization and jihad/savagery that's becoming more and more clearly delineated with every WTC or Bali or Nigeria or Afghanistan that we read about.  When the bloodthirsty Christian regimes ruled Europe and, by extension, much of the world with an iron fist, they were eventually toppled only by a stronger fist.  History reflects how incredibly savage and primitive that theocracy was, and to claim that the theocracies that exist in underindustrialized nations today are any less dangerous is folly.  The frightening fact is that today, instead of swords and horses, they have sarin, or enriched uranium, or smallpox.<br>
<br>
Despise me if you like, but I'm not willing to risk the well-being of my family, friends, or countrymen on the perceived kindness of strangers.  Sooner or later, someone needs to say enough is enough, and all the open-minded objectivity and good intentions in the world don't mean squat when you're dealing with a culture based in violence and insanity.     <br>
